Abstract (prophetic)

Cell Summary (no longer than 150 words)

The Cannabis sativa L. genome has coevolved with human culture over thousands of years as a source of food, fiber, and therapeutic compounds. The ~700 Mbp genome is organized into nine pairs of autosomes and as pair of sex chromosomes where genes are predominantly located near the ends of each chromosome. The majority of each chromosome is occupied by complete and fragmented repetitive elements occupying ~70% of the genome, a level comparable to maize. Predominant among the intact repetitive elements are Gypsy long terminal repeat elements. Within this expanse of repetitive sequences, each chromosome includes a metacentric or acrocentric chromosome. Understanding the genomic landscape within Cannabis that has evolved along with human culture may help us to better appreciate these cultural ties as well as guide its agronomic future.

Keywords: Cannabis, Cannabinoid synthase, hemp, Long Terminal Repeat (LTR) retrotransposon.


Brians notes

The term gypsy has been used in genetics to refer to a class of Long Terminal Repeat (LTR) retrotransposon. The term gyspy is also increasingly recognized as a pejorative term for the Romani people. Here we retain the use of this term because the genetics community has yet to agree on an alternative. We would also like to acknowledge that an alternate terminology may be more appropriate in the future.

  • Gene density
  • LTRs, gypsy
  • Cannabinoids
  • Sex chromosome
  • Terpenes
  • Disease ressistance (powdery mildew)
  • Chemotype: THCAS, THCAS:CBDAS, CBDAS, CBG, cannabinoid free
  • Chromosome/Genome length variability
  • PanGenome
    • Diversity of gene classes (cannabinoids, terpenes, disease resistance)?
  • Short day / day neutral

nucs <- read.csv("EH23a.softmasked_nuccomp.csv")

nucs$GC <- rowSums( nucs[, c("C", "c", "G", "g")] )/rowSums( nucs[, c("A", "a", "C", "c", "G", "g", "T", "t")] )
nucs$GC <- nucs$GC * 100
#nucs[1:3, ]
wins <- read.csv("EH23a.softmasked_wins1e6.csv")
#wins <- read.csv("EH23a.softmasked_wins1e7.csv")
wins$CGs <- 0
for( i in unique(wins$Id) ){
  wins$CGs[ wins$Id == i] <- wins$CG[ wins$Id == i] - min(wins$CG[ wins$Id == i], na.rm = TRUE)
  wins$CGs[ wins$Id == i] <- wins$CGs[ wins$Id == i]/max(wins$CGs[ wins$Id == i], na.rm = TRUE)
}

Circlize plot

plot_circlize <- function(){
  suppressPackageStartupMessages(library(circlize))
  
  par( mar = c(0, 0, 0, 0))
  #par( mar = c(5, 4, 4, 2))
  
  circos.par( start.degree = 90, 
              gap.after = c(rep(0, times = 9), 8)
              #gap.after = 10
            )

  circos.genomicInitialize( 
    data = myBed,
    axis.labels.cex =  0.4 * par("cex"),
    labels.cex = 0.8 * par("cex") 
  )
  
  circos.trackHist( 
    sectors = as.factor(genes$seqid),
    x = genes$start,
    track.height = 0.2,
    bg.border = "#FFFFFF",
    bg.col = myBed$cols,
    col = "#808080",
    border = NA,
    breaks = seq(0, 1e9, by = 2e6) 
  )

  circos.trackHist( 
    sectors = as.factor(genes2$seqid),
    x = genes2$start,
    track.height = 0.2,
    bg.border = "#FFFFFF",
    bg.col = myBed$cols,
    col = "#808080",
    border = NA,
    breaks = seq(0, 1e9, by = 1e6)
#  breaks = seq(0, 1e9, by = 2e6) 
  )

  circos.track( 
    ylim = c(0, 1),
    bg.col = NA,
    bg.border = "#00000044",
    track.height = 0.20, bg.lty = 3, bg.lwd = 1)

  for( i in unique( wins$Id ) ){
    tmp <- wins[ wins$Id == i, ]
    circos.rect(
      xleft = tmp$Start,
      ybottom = 0,
      xright = tmp$End,
      ytop = tmp$CGs,
      sector.index = i,
      col = "#1E90FF66",
      border = "#1E90FF11",
      lwd = 4
    )
  }

  for( i in unique( cann_blst$sseqid ) ){
    tmp <- cann_blst[ cann_blst$sseqid == i, ]
    circos.rect(
      xleft = tmp$sstart,
      ybottom = 0.8,
      xright = tmp$send,
      ytop = 1.0,
      sector.index = i,
      col = "#B2222244",
      border = "#B2222244",
#    border = NA,
      lwd = 2
    )
  }


  circos.track(
    ylim = c(0, 1),
    bg.col = NA,
    bg.border = "#00000044",
    track.height = 0.10, bg.lty = 3, bg.lwd = 1)

  for( i in unique( wins$Id ) ){
    tmp <- wins[ wins$Id == i, ]
    circos.rect(
      xleft = tmp$Start,
      ybottom = 0,
      xright = tmp$End,
    #ytop = tmp$cent370s,
      ytop = tmp$cent237s,
      sector.index = i,
      col = "#1E90FF66",
      border = "#1E90FF11",
      lwd = 4
    )
  }
  
  circos.yaxis( side = "left", 
                at = seq(0, 400, by = 50), 
                labels = c("", "", "", "", "A", "", ""),
                sector.index =  "EH23a.chr1",
                track.index = 2)
#circos.yaxis( side = "left", at = c(0, 180, 290), labels = c("", "A", ""), sector.index =  "EH23a.chr1", track.index = 2)
  circos.yaxis( side = "left", 
                at = seq(0, 20, by = 5), 
                labels = c("", "", "B", "", ""), 
                sector.index =  "EH23a.chr1", 
                track.index = 3)
#circos.yaxis( side = "left", at = c(0, 0.5, 1), labels = c("", "B", ""), sector.index =  "EH23a.chr1", track.index = 3)
#circos.yaxis( side = "left", at = c(0, 1000, 2000), labels = c("", "C", ""), sector.index =  "EH23a.chr1", track.index = 4)
  circos.yaxis( side = "left", 
                at = c(0, 0.5, 1), 
                labels = c("", "C", ""), 
                sector.index =  "EH23a.chr1",
                track.index = 4)
  circos.yaxis( side = "left", 
                at = c(0, 0.5, 1), 
                labels = c("", "D", ""), 
                sector.index =  "EH23a.chr1", 
                track.index = 5)
  
  myLeg <- rep("", times = 10)
  myLeg[c(2, 9)] <- c("High GC%", "Low GC%")

  legend('bottomleft',
       legend = myLeg,
       fill = viridisLite::magma(n=10, alpha = 0.4, begin = 1.0, end = 0.2),
       border = NA,
       pt.cex = 2,
       bty = "n", y.intersp = 0.5)

  title( main = "EH23a", line = -1 )

  circos.clear()
}

Figure 1. Genomic architecture of the Cannabis sativa genome. (Panel A) Circular representation of the strain ERBxHO40_23 haplotype a assembly. (A) Gene density, the background of each panel is colored by GC content (legend in lower left corner). (B) Density of the motif CG (also referred to as CpG, a motif associated with methylation). (C) Cannabis centromere motif density (370bp motif, blastn hits). (Panel B) Ideogram of the hemp genome. Chromosomes are named according to the CBDRx assembly (NCBI: GCF_900626175.2_cs10). Each autosomal ideogram summarizes the length of assemblies from 69 strains. The ideogram for the X chromosome summarizes the length of X chromosomal assemblies from 65 strains. The Y chromosomal ideogram summarizes the length of Y chromosomal assemblies from 4 strains. (Panel C) A Y chromosome panel? The strain ERBxHO40 resulted from a cross between strains ERB (type III or CBD dominant) and HO40 (type I or THC dominant; a genetically female plant (XX) that was chemically masculinized to produce pollen flowers to facilitate the cross).

wins <- read.csv("EH23a.softmasked_wins1e6.csv")
#wins <- read.csv("EH23a.softmasked_wins1e7.csv")
wins$CGs <- 0
for( i in unique(wins$Id) ){
  wins$CGs[ wins$Id == i] <- wins$CG[ wins$Id == i] - min(wins$CG[ wins$Id == i], na.rm = TRUE)
  wins$CGs[ wins$Id == i] <- wins$CGs[ wins$Id == i]/max(wins$CGs[ wins$Id == i], na.rm = TRUE)
}

cwin <- wins[wins$CGs == 1 & is.na(wins$CG) == FALSE, -c(6:9)]
cwin$CGp <- 2*cwin$CG/cwin$Win_length
cwin <- cwin[!duplicated(cwin$Id, ), ]
